ds and the words of her contemporaries, both friend and foe, they reveal a woman who lived according to the noble standardsof her time. She enjoyed the hunt, she practised her faith, and she tried to help or protect those who called upon her for assistance, as was expected of a queen and "good lady". Henry's mental breakdown, the birth of their son and growing tensions among the lords of the land forced her to step outside the life she would have expected to live. This study of Margaret's letters establishes the scope of a late medieval queen's concerns, while providing a unique account of this extraordinary woman. HELEN MAURER and B.M. CRON are both independent scholars; their work has focussed on Margaret of Anjou for many years.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aQueensvBiographyvCorrespondencezGreat Britain. 0aQueenszGreat BritainvBiographyvCorrespondence. 4aMedieval History. 4aMedieval Literature. 7aHISTORY / Medieval.2bisacsh  aHundred Years War.  aQueenship.  aWars of the Roses.  amedieval women.  awomen and power.1 aCron, B.M., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aMaurer, Helen E, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertBoydell and Brewer Complete eBook-Package 2019z978311143102440uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9781787445666?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781787445666423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781787445666/original  a978-3-11-143102-4  Boydell and Brewer Complete eBook-Package 2019b2019  aGBV-deGruyter-alles